<li id="cite_note-107"><b><a href="#cite_ref-107" title="">^</a></b> The proprtion of maternity dens on sea ice has changed from 62% between the years 1985–1994, to 37% over the years 1998–2004. The Alaskan population thus now more resembles the world population, in that it is more likely to den on land.<cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFFischbachAmstrupDouglas2007">Fischbach, A. S.; Amstrup, S. C.; Douglas, D. C. (October 2007), "Landward and eastward shift of Alaskan polar bear denning associated with recent sea ice changes", <i>Polar Biology</i> (Berlin: Springer) <b>30</b> (11): 1395–1405, <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<span class="neverexpand"><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1007%2Fs00300-007-0300-4" class="external text" title="http://dx.doi.org/10.1007%2Fs00300-007-0300-4" rel="nofollow">10.1007/s00300-007-0300-4</a></span></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Landward+and+eastward+shift+of+Alaskan+polar+bear+denning+associated+with+recent+sea+ice+changes&amp;rft.jtitle=Polar+Biology&amp;rft.aulast=Fischbach&amp;rft.aufirst=A.+S.&amp;rft.au=Fischbach%2C+A.+S.&amp;rft.au=Amstrup%2C+S.+C.&amp;rft.au=Douglas%2C+D.+C.&amp;rft.date=October+2007&amp;rft.volume=30&amp;rft.issue=11&amp;rft.pages=1395%E2%80%931405&amp;rft.place=Berlin&amp;rft.pub=Springer&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1007%2Fs00300-007-0300-4&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Polar_bear"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span>.</li>
